Name: DIISONONYL PHTHALATE
Description: Diisononyl phthalate is the diisononyl ester of benzene-1,2-dicarboxylic acid. It has a role as a plasticiser. It is a phthalate ester and a diester.

plant_concentrations.Value: Diisononyl phthalate was found in aquatic organisms June to Sept 1999 from False Harbor, Vancouver, British Columbia. The concentration in green algae (Enteromorpha intestinalis) was 3.44 ng/g lipid and in brown algae (Nereocysitis luetkeana, Fucus gardneri) was 2.88 ng/g lipid(1).

animal_concentrations.Value: Diisononyl phthalate concentrations in surf scoters (Melanitta perspicillata) sampled from June to Sept 1999 in False Harbor, Vancouver, British Columbia was 2.41 ng/g lipid(1). Concentrations in plankton (composite of phytoplankton, zooplakton and other pelagic invertebrates) sampled was 4.04 ng/g lipid(1).

Stockholm, Sweden: Inst Vatten-Och Luftvaardsfordkning (1995) (2) Malisch R, Schulte E, Acker L; Chem Ztg 105: 187-94 (1981) (3) Bjorklund K et al; Sci Total Environ 407: 4665-72 (2009)
sediment_soil_concentrations.Value: SEDIMENT: Diisononyl phthalate was identified, not quantified, in surface sediment of a lake in Sweden(1). Concentrations of diisononyl phthalate in sediments from 4 sites on the Rhine River in Germany were 30, 220, 625, and 1460 ppb(2). Concentrations from 3 sites on the Necker River were 430, 570, and 1050 ppb(2). Diisononyl phthalate was detected at a maximum of 200 ug/g dry weight in sediment from 3 urban run-off catchment basins in Sweden(3).
